---
import PageShell from '../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'UAE Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-requirements', text: 'Visa Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-plans', text: 'Recommended Plans', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global in UAE', href: '/countries/uae/insurance/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Allianz Care in UAE', href: '/countries/uae/insurance/allianz-care' },
  { title: 'BUPA Global in UAE', href: '/countries/uae/insurance/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Aetna International in UAE', href: '/countries/uae/insurance/aetna-international' },
  { title: 'Best Expat Insurance', href: '/best/expat-health-insurance' },
];

const planColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'type', header: 'Type' },
  { key: 'dhaCompliant', header: 'DHA Compliant' },
  { key: 'startingPrice', header: 'From' },
];

const planRows = [
  { provider: 'Daman', type: 'Local', dhaCompliant: true, startingPrice: '$100/mo' },
  { provider: 'Oman Insurance', type: 'Local', dhaCompliant: true, startingPrice: '$90/mo' },
  { provider: 'AXA Gulf', type: 'Regional', dhaCompliant: true, startingPrice: '$120/mo' },
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', type: 'International', dhaCompliant: true, startingPrice: '$200/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', type: 'International', dhaCompliant: true, startingPrice: '$150/mo' },
  { provider: 'BUPA Global', type: 'International', dhaCompliant: true, startingPrice: '$250/mo' },
  { provider: 'Aetna International', type: 'International', dhaCompliant: true, startingPrice: '$220/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Expats in UAE"
  description="Guide to health insurance for expats in UAE (Dubai, Abu Dhabi). Understand mandatory requirements, DHA compliance, and the best providers for expats."
  headline="Health Insurance for Expats in UAE"
  subheadline="Everything you need to know about health coverage in the UAE, including mandatory insurance requirements and top providers."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/countries/uae-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare UAE-Compliant Plans"
  ctaButtonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
  <p>
    The UAE has one of the world's largest expat populations—over 80% of residents are foreign nationals. Health insurance is mandatory for all residents, and the requirements vary by emirate. Dubai and Abu Dhabi have the strictest regulations.
  </p>
  <p>
    For expats, this means you must have compliant health insurance to obtain and maintain your residence visa. Employers are legally required to provide coverage, but many expats supplement employer plans or need to arrange their own coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Moving to UAE?"
    description="Find plans that meet UAE visa requirements and provide comprehensive coverage."
    buttonText="See UAE-Compliant Plans"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">UAE Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    The UAE has world-class healthcare facilities, particularly in Dubai and Abu Dhabi. Private hospitals offer cutting-edge technology and attract top medical professionals from around the world.
  </p>

  <h3>Public Healthcare</h3>
  <p>
    UAE citizens receive free or heavily subsidized healthcare through government facilities. Expats can use public hospitals but must pay, and public facilities are often more crowded than private options.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Healthcare</h3>
  <p>
    Most expats use private healthcare in the UAE. Benefits include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>World-class facilities (Cleveland Clinic Abu Dhabi, American Hospital Dubai)</li>
    <li>Short wait times</li>
    <li>English-speaking staff</li>
    <li>Latest medical technology</li>
    <li>JCI-accredited hospitals</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The downside is cost—UAE private healthcare is expensive, making insurance essential.
  </p>

  <h3>Key Healthcare Hubs</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Dubai Healthcare City:</strong> Free zone with 160+ medical facilities</li>
    <li><strong>Abu Dhabi:</strong> Cleveland Clinic Abu Dhabi, world-class facilities</li>
    <li><strong>Dubai:</strong> American Hospital, Mediclinic, Emirates Hospital</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Insurance Requirements</h2>
  <p>
    Health insurance is mandatory for all UAE residents. Requirements vary by emirate:
  </p>

  <h3>Dubai (DHA Requirements)</h3>
  <p>
    The Dubai Health Authority (DHA) mandates health insurance for all visa holders. Requirements:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Employers must provide</strong> coverage for employees</li>
    <li><strong>Sponsors must provide</strong> coverage for dependents</li>
    <li><strong>Minimum coverage:</strong> AED 150,000 (~$41,000) annual limit</li>
    <li><strong>Must include:</strong> Emergency care, maternity (for female dependents), basic tests</li>
    <li><strong>Must use DHA-approved insurer</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-yellow-50 border border-yellow-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-yellow-800">
      <strong>Important:</strong> Your insurance must be from a DHA-approved provider. Verify compliance before relying on any plan for visa purposes.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Abu Dhabi (HAAD/DOH Requirements)</h3>
  <p>
    Abu Dhabi's Department of Health (formerly HAAD) also mandates coverage:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Thiqa:</strong> Free coverage for UAE nationals</li>
    <li><strong>Daman Basic:</strong> Minimum plan for low-income workers</li>
    <li><strong>Enhanced plans:</strong> Required for higher-salary employees</li>
    <li>Coverage must be from an approved insurer</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Other Emirates</h3>
  <p>
    Sharjah, Ajman, Ras Al Khaimah, Fujairah, and Umm Al Quwain don't have mandatory insurance (yet), but most employers still provide it. Recommendations follow Dubai standards.
  </p>

  <h3>Golden Visa</h3>
  <p>
    UAE Golden Visa holders (10-year residency) must have health insurance. There's no specific coverage requirement, but having compliant insurance is essential for visa processing and renewal.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Need DHA-Compliant Insurance?"
    description="Compare plans from approved insurers that meet UAE requirements."
    buttonText="Compare Approved Plans"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="recommended-plans">Recommended Plans</h2>
  <p>
    Here are the most popular insurance options for expats in the UAE:
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={planColumns} rows={planRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>Local Plans</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Daman</strong> is the largest health insurer in the UAE and the only provider of the government's Thiqa program. They offer plans specifically designed for DHA/HAAD compliance.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Oman Insurance</strong> is another major local provider with competitive rates and strong UAE network coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Regional Plans</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>AXA Gulf</strong> offers plans tailored for the GCC region with competitive pricing and good coverage. They're DHA-approved and have a strong local network.
  </p>

  <h3>International Plans</h3>
  <p>
    International insurers offer worldwide coverage and portability:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong><a href="/countries/uae/insurance/cigna-global">Cigna Global</a></strong> — Most popular international choice, strong UAE network</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/countries/uae/insurance/allianz-care">Allianz Care</a></strong> — Modular plans with flexible options</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/countries/uae/insurance/bupa-global">BUPA Global</a></strong> — Premium coverage with excellent mental health benefits</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/countries/uae/insurance/aetna-international">Aetna International</a></strong> — Strong for US expats with US network access</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Employer vs Personal Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Most employers provide basic compliant coverage, but it may have limitations:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Lower coverage limits</li>
    <li>Limited hospital network</li>
    <li>Exclusions for certain treatments</li>
    <li>No worldwide coverage</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Many expats supplement employer plans or purchase personal international coverage for better protection and portability.
  </p>

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Costs</h2>
  <p>
    Healthcare and insurance costs in the UAE are relatively high:
  </p>

  <h3>Insurance Costs</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Basic DHA-compliant plans:</strong> $80-150/month</li>
    <li><strong>Mid-range local plans:</strong> $150-250/month</li>
    <li><strong>International plans:</strong> $200-500/month</li>
    <li><strong>Premium international coverage:</strong> $400-800/month</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Out-of-Pocket Costs (Without Insurance)</h3>
  <p>
    UAE healthcare is expensive without coverage:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>GP consultation:</strong> AED 200-500 ($55-135)</li>
    <li><strong>Specialist visit:</strong> AED 400-800 ($110-220)</li>
    <li><strong>Emergency room:</strong> AED 500-2,000+ ($135-545+)</li>
    <li><strong>Hospital stay:</strong> AED 2,000-5,000/day ($545-1,360/day)</li>
    <li><strong>Surgery:</strong> AED 20,000-100,000+ ($5,450-27,250+)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Cost Factors</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Age:</strong> Premiums increase significantly after 50</li>
    <li><strong>Coverage area:</strong> UAE-only vs worldwide</li>
    <li><strong>Deductible:</strong> Higher deductibles reduce premiums</li>
    <li><strong>Add-ons:</strong> Dental, maternity, wellness programs</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <h3>Is health insurance mandatory in UAE?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes, in Dubai and Abu Dhabi. Other emirates don't mandate it yet, but employers typically provide coverage anyway. You cannot obtain or renew a residence visa without valid health insurance.
  </p>

  <h3>Can I use my international insurance in UAE?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes, if your international plan is DHA/HAAD-approved. Major international insurers like Cigna, Allianz, BUPA, and Aetna have approval in the UAE. Always verify before relying on any plan for visa purposes.
  </p>

  <h3>What if my employer's insurance isn't enough?</h3>
  <p>
    You can purchase supplemental coverage or a personal international plan. Many expats do this for better hospital networks, higher limits, or worldwide coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Does UAE insurance cover me outside the country?</h3>
  <p>
    Local UAE plans typically don't cover you abroad. International plans provide worldwide coverage. If you travel frequently, international coverage is strongly recommended.
  </p>

  <h3>What about pre-existing conditions?</h3>
  <p>
    DHA regulations require coverage of pre-existing conditions for compliant plans, though there may be waiting periods or limitations. International plans vary—some offer full underwriting while others use moratorium underwriting.
  </p>

  <h3>Can I get insurance as a freelancer or remote worker?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. If you have a freelance visa or Golden Visa, you're responsible for your own insurance. International plans work well for this, and several DHA-approved options accept individual applicants.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Get Covered?"
    description="Compare plans from approved UAE insurers and international providers."
    buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. Insurance requirements and regulations change. We are not insurance brokers. Always verify DHA/HAAD compliance with your insurer before purchasing.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
